\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
title[Linearizing deformations with the spiral scattering transform]{Linearizing
 deformations of the harmonic source-filter model with the spiral scattering
 transform}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Vincent Lostanlen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
A classical model for voiced speech production consists in the convolution
 of a harmonic glottal source 
\begin_inset Formula $e(t)$
\end_inset

 with a vocal tract filter 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Introducing indepedent deformations to both components brings realistic
 variability to pitch and spectral envelope.
 We study the decomposition of the deformed source-filter model in the spiral
 scattering transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Deformations of the harmonic comb
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A real harmonic comb of dimensionless period 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is built as a sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 partials of integer frequencies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e(t)=\sum_{p=1}^{P}\cos(2\pi pt).
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\mathcal{C}^{3}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 a time warp function whose first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 is positive for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We defined a warped 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

source
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{\theta}(t)=\dot{\theta}(t)\times(e\circ\theta)(t)=\dot{\theta}(t)\times\sum_{p=1}^{P}\cos(2\pi p\theta(t)).
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the fundamental frequency of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Deformations of the broadband filter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)$
\end_inset

 be the impulse response of a broadband filter.
 Its Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is the spectral envelope, and is related to the properties of the vocal
 tract in speech production.
 Again, we define a time warp funtion 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in\mathcal{C}^{3}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\eta}(t)>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{\eta}(t)=\dot{\eta}(t)\times(h\circ\eta)(t).
\]

\end_inset

 Its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\eta}(t)$
\end_inset

 is a local dilation factor for the spectral envelope 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Deformed source-filter model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We extend the classical source filter model 
\begin_inset Formula $(e\ast h)(t)$
\end_inset

 by warping independently the source and the filter before comvolving them
 together:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{\text{\theta},\eta}(t)=(e_{\theta}\ast h_{\eta})(t).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Main result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will show that, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\eta}(t)$
\end_inset

 reasonably regular over the support of first-order wavelets 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)$
\end_inset

, the local maxima of spiral scattering coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}(t,\log\lambda_{1},\log\lambda_{2})$
\end_inset

 are clustered on a plane in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 space of scattering frequencies, where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 is the frequency along time, in Hertz.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the frequency along chromas, in cycles per octaves.
 Typically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert\beta\vert\geq1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the frequency across octaves, in cycles per octaves.
 Typically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert\gamma\vert\le1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This plane satisfies the Cartesian equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha+\dfrac{\ddot{\theta}(t)}{\dot{\theta}(t)}\beta+\dfrac{\ddot{\eta}(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\gamma=0.
\]

\end_inset

This result means that harmonic sounds overlapping both in time and frequency
 could be resolved according to their respective source-filter velocities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Outline of the proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our proof is organized as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assuming that the spectral envelope is almost constant over the frequential
 support of the wavelet, the convolution between 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}$
\end_inset

 can be factorized as a product between the Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}$
\end_inset

, up to a phase shift.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Interestingly, this result is a
\emph on
 swapped
\emph default
 formulationof the wavelet ridge theorem.
 Whereas the wavelet ridge theorem assumes that the signal has slowly varying
 amplitude and fundamental frequency over the support of the wavelet, here
 we assume that the wavelet has slowly varying amplitude over the support
 of the signal.
 Henceforth, the roles of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

analytic signal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

analytic wavelet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are interchanged.
 The form of the result remains the same.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 lowest partials in the harmonic comb do not interfere.
 Thus, we may apply the wavelet ridge theorem to each of them independently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Combining the two previous results yields a factorization of deformed source
 and deformed filter in the scalogram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The harmonicity property implies that the convolution along chromas only
 applies to the deformed source.
 In turn, the spectral smoothness property implies that the convolution
 across octaves only applies to the deformed filter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We use the wavelet ridge theorem to give the phase of the deformed source
 after convolution along chromas.
 The same theorem applies to the deformed filter after convolution across
 octaves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The two phase functions extracted in the previous part add up.
 Hence, after convolution along chromas and across octaves, the analytic
 amplitude and instantaneous frequency along time are available in closed
 form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We use the wavelet ridge theorem a third time to localize in time the relative
 variations of the two instantaneous frequencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Cartesian equation is derived from the extraction of spiral wavelet
 ridges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work under the following assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
twice more filters than partials within every octave: 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\geq P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
slowly varying source: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\ddot{\theta}/\dot{\theta}\Vert_{\infty}\ll\lambda_{1}/Q$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
slowly varying filter: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\ddot{\eta}/\dot{\eta}\Vert_{\infty}\ll\lambda_{1}/Q$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
spectral envelope is almost constant over one semitone: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\mathrm{d}(\log\vert\hat{h}\vert)/\mathrm{d}\omega\Vert_{\infty}\ll Q/\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
spectral envelope is almost linear over one octave: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\mathrm{d}(\log\vert\hat{h}\vert)/\mathrm{d}(\log\omega)\Vert_{\infty}\ll1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, we use the fact that harmonicity implies self-similarity: 
\begin_inset Formula $e(t)=e(2^{n}t)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert t\vert>2\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 By means of the Poisson summation formula, this rewrites in the Fourier
 domain as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{e}(\omega)=\hat{e}(2^{j}\omega)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert\omega\vert>1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Wavelet filter bank
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{g}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 be a real symmetric window of bandwidth 
\begin_inset Formula $1/Q$
\end_inset

 and unit norm.
 An approximately analytic wavelet is constructed by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 with a complex sine wave of dimensionless frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(t)=g(t)\exp(\mathrm{i}t).
\]

\end_inset

We define 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

 as the typical time support of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of a Gaussian bell curve 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t),$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}$
\end_inset

 of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $4Q$
\end_inset

.
 Dilated wavelets are written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)=\lambda_{1}\psi(\lambda_{1}t).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The role of the wavelet transform is to localize the power spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 along short-term windows 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)$
\end_inset

 of size 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}/\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 upon which both time warps 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t)$
\end_inset

 can be linearized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Wavelet ridge theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following theorem provides an approximate closed form for the wavelet
 transform of a real analytic signal whose amplitude and instantaneous frequency
 have slow variations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)=a(t)\cos\varphi(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The wavelet transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 with the wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)=g(\lambda_{1}t)\exp(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}t)$
\end_inset

 is equal to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(f\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\right)(t)=\dfrac{1}{2}a(t)\exp(\mathrm{i}\varphi(t))\times\left(\hat{g}\left(1-\dfrac{\dot{\varphi}(t)}{\lambda_{1}}\right)+\varepsilon(t,\lambda_{1})\right).
\]

\end_inset

The corrective term satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon(t,\lambda_{1})\leq\left\Vert \dfrac{\dot{a}(t)}{\lambda_{1}a(t)}\right\Vert _{t,T_{g}/\lambda_{1}}+\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{a}(t)}{\lambda_{1}^{2}a(t)}\right\Vert _{t,T_{g}/\lambda_{1}}+\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{\varphi}(t)}{\lambda_{1}^{2}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{g}/\lambda_{1}}+\sup_{\vert\omega\vert\geq\vert\dot{\varphi}\vert(t)/\lambda_{1}}\vert\hat{g}(\omega)\vert,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\cdot\Vert_{t,T_{g}/\lambda_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is a shorthand for the supremum norm over the time support 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{g}/\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 of the wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)$
\end_inset

, e.g.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \dfrac{\dot{a}(t)}{\lambda_{1}a(t)}\right\Vert _{t,T_{g}/\lambda_{1}}=\sup_{\left|u-t\right|<T_{g}/\lambda_{1}}\left|\dfrac{\dot{a}(u)}{\lambda_{1}\dot{a}(u)}\right|.
\]

\end_inset

The fourth term is negligible if 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\text{\varphi}}(t)\geq\lambda_{1}/Q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof can be found in Mallat's Wavelet Tour, section 4.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linearization of filter deformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathbf{L^{2}}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 of finite support 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in\mathcal{C}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\eta}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The wavelet transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\eta}(t)=\dot{\eta}(t)\times(h\circ\eta)(t)$
\end_inset

 with the wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)=g(\lambda_{1}t)\times\exp(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}t)$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}})(t)=\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\left(\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\times\hat{h}\left(\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)+\varepsilon(t,\lambda_{1}).
\]

\end_inset

The corrective term satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dfrac{\vert\varepsilon(t,\lambda_{1})\vert}{\lambda_{1}T_{h}\Vert h\Vert_{\infty}}\leq T_{h}^{2}g\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{\eta}}{\dot{\eta}^{3}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}+\dot{g}\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\left\Vert \dfrac{1}{\dot{\eta}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}+\lambda_{1}\left\Vert \ddot{g}\right\Vert _{\infty}\left\Vert \dfrac{1}{\dot{\eta}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\cdot\Vert_{t,T_{h}}$
\end_inset

 is a shorthand for the supremum norm over the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert f\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}=\sup_{\left|u-t\right|<T_{h}}\vert f(u)\vert.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The convolution between the deformed filter and the wavelet is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}})(t)=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\dot{\eta}(u)\times\left(h\circ\eta\right)(u)\times\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t-u)\,\mathrm{d}u.
\]

\end_inset

The change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\eta(u)$
\end_inset

 leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}})(t)=\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}h(v)\times\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right)\,\mathrm{d}v,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{(-1)}$
\end_inset

 is the functional inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

.
 We compute the second-order Taylor expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{(-1)}$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta^{(-1)}(v)=t+\dfrac{\left(v-\eta(t)\right)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}+\dfrac{\left(v-\eta(t)\right)^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}\left(v\right)
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\right|\leq\sup_{\left[t,\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right]}\left|\dfrac{\ddot{\eta}}{\dot{\eta}^{3}}\right|.
\]

\end_inset

The wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is built with the analytic form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right)=g\left(\lambda_{1}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right)\right)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

Let us define the auxiliary function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(v)=-\dfrac{v}{\dot{\eta}(t)}-\dfrac{\left(v-\eta(t)\right)^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}\left(v\right).\label{eq:rho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(\lambda_{1}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right)\right)=g\left(\lambda_{1}\left(\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}+\rho(v)\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset

We expand the envelope 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 again with a second-order Taylor expansion around 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
g\left(\lambda_{1}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right)\right) & = & g\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\\
 & + & \lambda_{1}\dot{g}\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\times\rho(v)\\
 & + & \dfrac{\lambda_{1}^{2}\rho(v)^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{g}\left(\rho(v)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and make the crude majorization
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\varepsilon_{g}\left(\rho(v)\right)\right|\leq\sup_{\mathbb{R}}\vert\ddot{g}\vert.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
 & \left(h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\right)(t)\times\exp\left(-\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\\
= & g\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right){\displaystyle \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}h(v)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}v\right)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\left(v-\eta(t)\right)^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\right)\;\mathrm{d}v & \text{(I)}\\
- & \lambda_{1}\dot{g}\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right){\displaystyle \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}\rho(v)h(v)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}v\right)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\left(v-\eta(t)\right)^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\right)\;\mathrm{d}v & \text{(II)}\\
+ & \dfrac{\lambda_{1}^{2}}{2}{\displaystyle \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}\rho(v)^{2}\varepsilon_{g}(\rho(v))h(v)\exp\left(-\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)-\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\right)\;\mathrm{d}v. & \text{(III)}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

A first-order Taylor expansion of the complex exponential gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{exp}\left(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\dfrac{v^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\right)=1+\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\dfrac{v^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\varepsilon_{\mathrm{exp}}(v)\label{eq:complex-exp-linearization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varepsilon_{\mathrm{exp}}(v)\right|\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 We recognize the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v)$
\end_inset

 evaluated at the negative frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $-\lambda_{1}/\dot{\eta}(t)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}h(v)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}v\right)\;\mathrm{d}v=\hat{h}\left(-\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v)$
\end_inset

 is real, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, so we may drop the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}/\dot{\eta}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The first term in the expansion rewrites as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{(I)}=g\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\left(\hat{h}\left(\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)+\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\lambda_{1}\dfrac{v^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\varepsilon_{\mathrm{exp}}(v)\;\mathrm{d}v\right).
\]

\end_inset

Inserting Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:complex-exp-linearization"

\end_inset

 in the expression of Equation yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\left(h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\right)(t)-\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\left(\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\hat{h}\left(\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\right|\leq\varepsilon_{\text{(I)}}+\varepsilon_{\text{(II)}}+\varepsilon_{\text{(III)}}
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{\mathrm{(I)}}=\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{2}\left|{\displaystyle \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}h(v)v^{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\varepsilon_{\mathrm{exp}}(v)\;\mathrm{d}v\right|,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{\text{(II)}}=\lambda_{1}\dot{g}\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\left|{\displaystyle \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}\rho(v)h(v)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}v\right)\exp\left(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\left(v-\eta(t)\right)^{2}}{2}\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)\right)\;\mathrm{d}v\right|,
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{\text{(III)}}=\dfrac{\lambda_{1}^{2}}{2}\left|{\displaystyle \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}}\rho(v)^{2}\varepsilon_{g}(\rho(v))h(v)\exp\left(-\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}\left(t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)-\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\right)\;\mathrm{d}v\right|.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}$
\end_inset

 be the time support of the filter 
\begin_inset Formula $h(t)$
\end_inset

.
 We dominate all three corrective terms with a simple 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

base times height
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inequality and with complex exponentials replaced by quadratic surrogates.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}$
\end_inset

 is dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(v)$
\end_inset

 is dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert h\Vert_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\eta^{(-1)}}(v)$
\end_inset

 is dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{\eta}}{\dot{\eta}^{3}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{\text{(I)}}\leq\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{2}\times T_{h}^{2}\times\Vert h\Vert_{\infty}\times\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{\eta}}{\dot{\eta}^{3}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}\times T_{h}.
\]

\end_inset

We have, by first order expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta^{(-1)}(v)$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vert\rho(v)\vert\leq\left\Vert t-\eta^{(-1)}(v)\right\Vert _{\infty}\leq\left\Vert \dfrac{1}{\dot{\eta}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}.
\]

\end_inset

Plugging this inequality into the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{(\mathrm{II})}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\varepsilon_{\mathrm{(II)}} & \leq & \lambda_{1}\dot{g}\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\times\left\Vert \dfrac{1}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}\times\Vert h\Vert_{\infty}\times T_{h}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We dominate 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{\mathrm{(III)}}$
\end_inset

 in the same way: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\varepsilon_{\text{(III)}} & \leq & \dfrac{\lambda_{1}^{2}}{2}\times\left\Vert \dfrac{1}{\dot{\eta}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}^{2}\times\Vert\ddot{g}\Vert_{\infty}\times\Vert h\Vert_{\infty}\times T_{h}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\varepsilon_{\mathrm{(I)}}+\varepsilon_{\mathrm{(II)}}+\varepsilon_{\mathrm{(III)}}$
\end_inset

 be the full corrective term.
 We conclude with the desired upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linearization of source deformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta,\nu\in\mathcal{C}^{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\nu}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\theta}(t)=\dot{\theta}(t)\times\sum_{p=1}^{P}\cos(2\pi p\theta(t))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\eta}=\dot{\eta}(t)\times(h\circ\eta)(t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\mathbf{L^{2}}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 is of finite support 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 The wavelet transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\theta,\eta}(t)=(e_{\theta}\ast h_{\eta})(t)$
\end_inset

 with the wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)=g(\lambda_{1}t)\exp(\mathrm{i}\lambda_{1}t)$
\end_inset

 is equal to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(e_{\theta}\ast h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\right)(t)=\varepsilon+\hat{h}\left(\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\times\sum_{p=1}^{P}\exp(\mathrm{i}p\dot{\theta}(t))\times\widehat{\psi}\left(\dfrac{p\dot{\theta}(t)}{\lambda_{1}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We start by applying the above lemma:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(e_{\theta}\ast h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\right)(t) & = & e_{\theta}\ast\left(h_{\eta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\right)(t)\\
 & = & e_{\theta}\ast\left(\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\left(\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\times\hat{h}\left(\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)+\varepsilon_{h}(t,\lambda_{1})\right),\\
 & = & \hat{h}\left(\dfrac{\lambda_{1}}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\times\left(e_{\theta}\ast\psi_{\lambda_{1}}\right)\left(\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)+\left(e_{\theta}\ast\varepsilon_{h}\right)(t,\lambda_{1}).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We have shown that the corrective term 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{h}$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dfrac{\vert\varepsilon(t,\lambda_{1})\vert}{\lambda_{1}T_{h}\Vert h\Vert_{\infty}}\leq T_{h}^{2}g\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\left\Vert \dfrac{\ddot{\eta}}{\dot{\eta}^{3}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}+\dot{g}\left(\lambda_{1}\dfrac{\eta(t)}{\dot{\eta}(t)}\right)\left\Vert \dfrac{1}{\dot{\eta}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}+\lambda_{1}\left\Vert \ddot{g}\right\Vert _{\infty}\left\Vert \dfrac{1}{\dot{\eta}}\right\Vert _{t,T_{h}}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

